KASTIYA — THE NORTHERN PORT MAP: 16:9 NEO‑UKIYO‑E MASTERPIECE
(Upload your Northern Vale regional map as a strict reference for the port’s precise location on the northeastern coast, where the Frozen Sea meets the Vale, and the trade routes converge.)

1. REFERENCE IMAGE & GEOGRAPHICAL FIDELITY
Take the uploaded Northern Vale map as an absolute geographical stencil for Kastiya and its immediate, ice‑bound maritime environs. Zoom into the northeastern coast of the Vale, where the frozen shoreline forms a deep, sheltered natural harbour, the only safe anchorage for miles of glacial cliffs. Maintain with surgical precision the port’s exact position relative to the Frozen Sea (north and east), the distant, ethereal spires of the Magic Academy (far east, across the water), and the warm, holy glow of the Great Martyr Shrine (south‑west). Do not alter, move, or distort the coastline, the harbour’s shape, or the ancient, ice‑scoured trade routes that lead inland. Kastiya must sit exactly where it is placed on your reference map. The only transformation permitted is a massive increase in detail: every ice‑locked dock, every warming stone‑built warehouse, every spectral mast and tattered sail, and the ghastly, imposing silhouette of the undead pirate lord must now blossom into a fully realised, hyper‑detailed port of frozen commerce and cursed revenge, faithful to the established lore of the Northern Vale’s maritime lifeline and the terror that haunts it.

2. CANVAS & COMPOSITION
Generate a 16:9 horizontal image (1920×1080 pixels). Kastiya fills the central and right portion of the frame, a rugged, sheltered harbour carved into the dark, jagged cliffs of the northeastern coast. The foreground is the icy, stone‑paved docks, busy with tiny, fur‑swaddled silhouettes. The left and top edges open onto the vast, pale cerulean‑grey expanse of the Frozen Sea, where icebergs drift and the distant, faint ribbon of the Aurora Borealis shimmers on the horizon. The background is the rising, snow‑capped mountains of the Vale interior. The entire map is presented as a salt‑crusted, ice‑rimed cartographic scroll — as if drawn by a terrified harbourmaster who witnessed the ghost fleet’s return, capturing the commerce of the living and the terror of the damned. All major landmarks are labelled in elegant English cartographic script.

3. STYLE: NEO‑UKIYO‑E WITH SUMI‑E INK WASH (THE AESTHETIC OF THE FROZEN SEA)
The entire map is rendered in an uncompromising fusion of Neo‑Ukiyo‑e woodblock aesthetics and Zen Sumi‑e ink‑wash techniques, adapted for a realm of ice‑locked commerce, spectral maritime terror, and the deep, cold mystery of the northern ocean. The brushwork is a study in contrasts: the sturdy, warm‑lit stone of the port buildings is rendered in precise, angular dry‑brush strokes of charcoal and ochre, the sea is a layered, glacial wash of pale cerulean, silver, and deep indigo, and the ghostly ship and the kraken are painted in eerie, wet‑on‑wet washes of spectral teal and abyssal black. The port is built of layered washes of cold granite‑grey, warm amber (from the lit windows), sea‑spray silver, and the sickly, bioluminescent teal‑green of Bane’s cursed aura. The parchment base is a cold, sea‑stained ivory, stiff with salt. Raised silver lacquer is used for the ice and the ghost ship’s spectral rigging, tarnished gold for Bane’s pirate finery, and the eerie, glowing teal for his eyes and the kraken’s tentacles. Every element is executed with 8K‑grade texture fidelity, feeling simultaneously like a captain’s log and a living, breathing port on the edge of the frozen world.

4. THE NEO‑UKIYO‑E BORDER — THE CORAL‑AND‑ANCHOR RELIQUARY
The map is enclosed in a single, rugged, maritime border befitting the northern port. Its outermost edge is a hairline of rusted, salt‑pitted iron, heavy and cold. Inside runs a continuous register of stylised, intertwining anchor‑chain and ice‑crystal motifs, rendered in raised, matte charcoal and pale silver lacquer. Interwoven with the chains are the silhouettes of barnacles, frozen seaweed, and the occasional, ghostly tentacle of the kraken. At the four corners, the border transforms into ornate, nautical compass medallions: a great, barnacle‑encrusted anchor (northwest), a spectral, skeletal shark breaching (northeast), a ghost ship’s wheel, shattered (southwest), and a single, glowing teal octopus eye (southeast). The innermost edge is a rough, wet‑brush enso of sea‑grey sumi, its edges bleeding like a wave on ice — a meditation on the greed, the depths, and the pact that defies death.

5. THE LANDSCAPE — ZOOMED‑IN, HYPER‑DETAILED KASTIYA & THE GHOST FLEET
The port and its immediate waters are a breathtaking, tense tapestry of mortal industry and the supernatural terror that lurks just offshore.

The Ice‑Locked Harbour (The Living Port): The right and central foreground is the bustling harbour of Kastiya. Its stone piers are encrusted with thick, translucent ice, their surfaces worn by the sledges of fur‑wrapped traders. Massive, stone‑built warehouses with steep, snow‑laden roofs and glowing, amber‑lit windows line the waterfront. Tiny docker, fisherman, and trader silhouettes in heavy furs can be seen hauling frozen fish, rolling barrels, and leading shaggy, northern ponies. A sturdy, stone lighthouse, the Beacon of the North, stands at the harbour’s mouth, its great fire casting a warm, defiant gold beam across the ice.

The Frozen Anchorage (The Waters of the Damned): The left and centre‑left of the canvas is the open water of the Frozen Anchorage, a patch of deep, indigo‑black sea that refuses to fully freeze, kept open by a dark, unnatural warmth. Massive, jagged icebergs drift slowly, their submerged forms glowing with a faint, eerie teal. This is where the ghost fleet anchors. The water’s surface is broken by the faint, spectral outlines of sunken treasure galleons far below.

The Phantom Fleet (Bane’s Armada): In the centre of the anchorage, dominating the water, is Bane’s Phantom Fleet. The flagship, a massive, barnacle‑encrusted ghost galleon, floats with tattered, ethereal black sails that shimmer with a sickly teal luminescence. Its hull is broken and skeletal, yet it holds together, cannons of dark, cursed iron protruding from its sides. Tiny, ghostly skeleton‑pirate silhouettes can be seen climbing the rigging.

The Kraken’s Mantle (The Living Cloak): Churning the water around the ghost ship are the massive, coiled tentacles of the Abyssal Kraken, Bane’s patron. The tentacles are a deep, bruised reddish‑orange with pale, glowing suction cups, rendered in glossy, raised lacquer. They do not attack the port; they writhe possessively around the ship, the monstrous extension of the pirate lord’s will.

Bane — The Lord of the Seven Seas (Tiny, Ghastly Silhouette): Standing defiantly on the bowsprit of his ghost galleon, his immense form silhouetted against the cold, aurora‑lit sky, is Bane himself. He is the undead terror, the scourge of the seas. His silhouette captures every detail of the description:

His head is entirely cephalopod in nature, a bright reddish‑orange octopus, with thick, muscular tentacles curling outward from his lower face like a beard, cinched with golden rings. His eyes are two piercing, luminous teal pinpoints.

He wears an oversized, classic black bicorne pirate hat with a prominent, stylized gold anchor emblem at the front.

